Coevolutionary Algorithms and Coevolving Agents
Workshop at the 1999 Genetic and Evolutionary Computation Conference ( GECCO- 99 )
Tuesday , 13 July 1999
Workshop outline
In solving complex tasks using evolutionary methods there are often many conflicting requirements , and there are many complexities in breaking down a complex problem into effective subproblems . It has been proposed that such complexities can be handled by coevolutionary interactions , such as cooperation , competition and host-parasite or predator-prey interaction .
This workshop will consider ways in which these coevolutionary processes can be applied to improving the performance of evolutionary algorithms , both in improving the performance of algorithms in existing problem domains and using the techniques to solve problems which are not amenable to conventional evolutionary computing techniques . Combining evolutionary computing ideas with the problem decomposition and distributed solution techniques which lie at the heart of innovations such as agent technology provide a powerful paradigm for problem solving in many domains . These techniques provide a cyber-diversity of problem-solving methods which echo the bio-diversity found in nature .
Possible topics for the workshop include :
Cooperation , coordination and competition ( CCC ) in evolutionary computing CCC in software agents and in robots Developing a theoretical basis for coevolutionary computing The effects of evolutionary theory on these topics Exploiting the computational power of artificial life systems Tools and systems for the practical realization of these techniques Emergent and endogenous fitness functions Analysis of what types of problems are amenable to these methods Emergence of societies and organizational structures Real-world applications
The format of the workshop will consist of a number of short talks , in which speakers will be invited both to describe work in this area and to raise questions for a discussion session . It is planned to publish a summary of the workshop as a supplement to the main Gecco 99 proceedings , including contributions from the organizers and the selected speakers , and this will be available at the conference .
Participation
It is anticipated that there will be time for 4 - 5 short talks , of approximately 10 - 15 minutes duration . This will leave approximately half the workshop time for discussion . To this aim , talks should aim to raise questions about the subject , and should not simply be presentations of existing results . The ideal talk would be a summary of some work which provokes some interesting ideas , together with a few questions to stimulate discussion .
People wishing to present a talk should send a paper of approximately 3 pages to the address below by 1 st March 1999 . Accepted papers will be published in a supplement to the conference proceedings . The preferred format for submission is postscript files by email . If anyone is unable to send a file in electronic form then please contact the organizers .
